Various forms of the Weyötiss verb.

Form I (simple present):

ο	̨ς	̨ι	τον	μιν	τ	ο̨νθ
ο̨μ	ο̨ς	ο̨	ο̨τον	ο̨μιν	ο̨τ	ο̨ιν
		το	τον		τ	ονθο		μιν

λυμο	λυ̨μς	λυ̨μι	λυντον	λυμμιν	λυντ	λυμο̨νθ
λυμο̨μ	λυμο̨ς	λυμο̨	λυμο̨τον	λυμο̨μιν	λυμο̨τ	λυμο̨ιν
	λυμ	λυντο	λυντον		λυντ	λυμονθο		λυμμιν

ηελο	ηελς	ηελα̨	ηελετον	ηελομιν	ηελετ	ηελο̨νθ
ηελο̨μ etc
	ηελε	ηελετο	ηελετον		ηελετ	ηελονθο		ηελεμιν

Note the aspirated final—this has merged phonetically, but is still written.
Note also that, by regular sound change, the 2sg optative should be λυμς. The /œ/ is restored by analogy. Same for the 3pl—/ɔi/ becomes /œi/.

I'm not sure about any other instances of analogy. The 3sg imperative could probably be lost and replaced with the 3pl, given the passive. But apart from that... I like most of the forms.

Form II (simple aorist):

	ς		τον	μιν	τ	ον
α̨μ	α̨ς	α̨	α̨τον	α̨μιν	α̨τ	α̨ιν
		το	τον		τ	ονθο		α̨

ελυς	ελυς	ελυς	ελυστον	ελυσμιν	ελυστ	ελυσον
λυσα̨μ	λυσα̨ς	λυσα̨	λυσα̨τον	λυσα̨μιν	λυσα̨τ	λυσα̨ιν
	λυσ	λυστο	λυστον		λυστ	λυσονθο		λυσα̨

ελιπ	ελιφς	ελιπ	ελιπτον	ελιμμιν	ελιπτ	ελιπον
λιπο̨μ	λιπο̨ς	λιπο̨	λιπο̨τον	λιπο̨μιν	λιπο̨τ	λιπο̨ν
	λιπ	λιπτο	λιπτον		λιπτ	λιπονθο		λιμμιν
ελαιφθιν, ελαιπτς (?), etc.

See the above note about the 2sg optative. Note that the indicative of the first and second aorists is identical after syncope, except for the 1sg. This is leveled in favor of the endingless form, because apparently this is German. The second-person imperative is leveled the other way, however, presumably by analogy with the present. Retaining it is seen as antiquated, and it is to that end sometimes added to the present form as well (there's probably a parallel with English -eth or -e or something?) Thus the only major difference between original first and second aorists is the vowel of the optative. This largely reflects the original split, but does tend to get confused occasionally.

I'm more than a little tempted to lower /ej/ to /aj/. 

Form III (perfect):

κ	χ	κ	κτον		κμιν		κτ	κα̨ντ
ο̨μ	ο̨ς	ο̨	ο̨τον		ο̨μιν		ο̨τ	ο̨ιν
		το	τον				τ	ονθο		μιν

λελυκ	λελυχ	λελυκ	λελυκτον	λελυκμιν	λελυκτ	λελυκα̨ντ
λελυο̨μ	λελυο̨ς	λελυο̨	λελυο̨τον	λελυο̨μιν	λελυο̨τ	λελυο̨ιν
	λελυ	λελυτο	λελυτον				λελυτ	λελυονθο	λελυμιν

λελο̨π	λελο̨πς	λελο̨π	λελο̨πτον	λελο̨μμιν	λελο̨πτ	λελο̨πον
λελο̨πο̨μ etc.
λελο̨π etc.									λελο̨μμιν

This is weird and probably doesn't have a good reason to remain so... untouched unless it gains some significant semantic load. I'm not sure what. We could be German and make it the default preterite?

There's also the option to fuse the periphrastic forms, but I don't really want to.

Form IV (future):

To be determined. If it exists it's not going to be too hard to use—there's only some verbs like πυνθάνω that will have a future stem different from both the present and aorist. And of course the endings are the same as the present.


Form V (do-present):

τθιμ	τιτς	τθιτ	τιττον	τιθμιν	τιττ	τθινθ
τθαιν	τθαις	τθαιε	τθαιτον	τθαιμιν	τθαιτ	τθαιιν
	τιθε	τιττο	τιττον		τιττ	τιθινθο		τιθμιν

This is used with the -σις derivative of the main verb. So: λυ̨σς τθιμ, λαιπς τιτς, etc.

Form VI (do-aorist):

εθικ	εθιχ	εθικ	εττον		εθμιν	εττε	εθον
θειν	θεις	θειε	θαιτον		θαιμιν	θαιτ	θειιν
	θε	θετο	θετον			θετ	θενθο		θεμιν

As above.

Form VIII (do-future):

The stem is θιση-. Not sure if we're doing this either.

Form IX (keep-present):

α	ευς	ει	αυτον	αμμιν	αυτ	ανθ
?
	α	αυτο	αυτον		αυτ	ανθο

The optative should probably be suppleted.

Other ideas for periphrases:

ἄγω + acc = "neut." verb
βαίνω + part = fut (only once)
εἰμί + part = finite verb
ἔρχομαι + διὰ + gen = verb
ποιέω (med.) + acc = verb
τίθημι + acc = verb
χρῶμαι + acc = verb

Of these, βαίνω and εἰμί are out, because participles are forbidden. ἄγω could be interesting if we have some sort of contraction rule (g > h, remember.) The forms of the present look like:

ahɔ, ɛxs, ɛhi, axtɔn, aŋmin, axt, ahœntʰ

ahɔ > aː with the h-tone. ɛxs could do an Anglo-Frisian and become ɛuxs > juxs/joxs > joks/jos (also with the h-tone?) axt(ɔn) could also break into auxt > aukt/aut. aŋmin is fine where it is (unless we want to do assimilate ŋm in the first place.) ɛhi > ɛi, which becomes ai (see form II/V/VI opt. pass.) ahœntʰ > aːntʰ I think. So:

a, jɔs, ai, autɔn, aŋmin, aut, antʰ

I don't like jɔs, and I also am leaning towards ŋm > mm. Instead of jos, let's just do ɛuxs > ɛys or whatever ευ does.

a, ɛys, ai, autɔn, ammin, aut, antʰ
α, αυ̨ς, αι, αυτον, αμμιν, αυτ, ανθ

The only modification I might make is spelling the 2sg/3sg ευς and ει. Otherwise this looks pretty good.

As to meaning, it apparently had an iterative meaning. Only the present is listed in LSJ. Thus there will be no aorist. This will be form IX.

That leaves ἔρχομαι, ποιέω, χρῶμαι. ποιέω is out because it's going to be the causative. ἔρχομαι might not be, though. The interesting forms are the aorist ἦλθον:

ευθ	ευτς	ευθ	ευτον	ευθμιν	ευτ	ευθον
ευθο̨μ	ευθο̨ς	ευθο̨	ευθο̨τον	ευθο̨μιν	ευθο̨τ	ευθο̨ν
	ευθ	ευτο	ευτον		ευτ	ευθονθο		ευθμιν

Okay, but.
There's a change lt(ʰ) > nt(ʰ) in certain areas. This would be nice because, well, l > w is good and all but less effective when ευ is already a non-transparent diphthong. Unfortunately, Boeotian is known not to have this change (and shouldn't be expected to—it's largely Peloponnesian). I'm tempted to do it anyway, but. We could try to make this interesting by not syncoping /u/, but I don't know that this will give me pretty forms.

Besides, the periphrases aren't convincing (three of the four examples are 'go into battle', and the fourth is 'go into fire'). If we do end up using this it'll be imperfective, I guess.

χράομαι is a contract. Even though it's χρέομαι outside of IA, I don't want to use it.

Present: habitual, gnomic, conative, future. The present is also used in narration and in prophecies. "Conative" is like inchoative, but describes an attempt to do something. Of these the 'conative' is by far the most interesting, and should therefore be regarded as the primary meaning, although it will certainly be necessary to use the simple present in other contexts, as I don't know how common the conative will actually be.

One of these contexts is the impersonal. It is decided. There will have to be others, though.

I guess the other context is 'subordinate clauses'. It's certainly prettier that way.

Future: gnomic, jussive. Neither one of these is really what I want, so we'll just keep it as a future.

Aorist: resultative, gnomic, empiric (?). With ἄν, iterative. The 1sg is used apparently statively "derived from familiar discourse, but is not found in good prose"—see 1937. I support condensing this to "gnomic" and something vaguely "perfect" (resulative and 1937 are pretty similar, and 1940 describes a similar usage.) Actually, let's make the regular one gnomic, and then the periphrastic one is perfect/resultative.

A similar thing happens with the present.

Perfect: empiric, and also something (1949) similar to the aorist (only one example in Smyth of each.) There is also a distinct leaning towards resultative rather than strictly perfect—cf. the many perfects used in a present sense. Our best bet is either 1949, or pulling a German. Both of these seem to come to the same thing, of course. I'm inclined to do this, because the imperfect is gone and the aorist is the gnomic/perfect now. (What does the do-aorist become?)

According, to LSJ, τίθημι periphrastic is used with these verbal nouns:

σκέδᾰσις - σκεδάννυμι
κρῠφός - κρῠπτω
νέμεσις - νέμω (?)
αἶνος - αἰνέω
σχολή - σχολάζω
σωτερία (?) - σῴζω (?) or προμήθεια - προμανθάνω
μάχη - μάχομαι
θῠσία - θῡω
γάμος - γαμέω
σπουδή - σπεύδω
πρόνοια - προνοέω
ἐπιστροφή - ἐπιστρέφω
οἰκονομία - οἰκονομέω
λησμοσύνη - λανθάνω
συγγνωμοσύνη - συγγιγνώσκω

So that's two with -σις, one with -ός, three with -ή (and one with -η), one with -ία, two with -ια, one with -σία (or θυσ- + ία?), two with -μοσύνη, two with -ος from which -έω is derived.

That is, there's no coherency.

-σις has the problem of neutralizing all the dentals. -ός/-ή is nice but not universal. -ια is p bad. -ία is better and has the advantage of doing umlaut, and also being in Caland systems. -μοσύνη is 'lyric'—it would be -μοτῡνα > νταυν, which is... okay I guess? but probably not the best.


