[size=150][b][u]Morphosyntax[/u][/b][/size]

Modern Weyötiss distinguishes roughly six TAMs. The former present has narrowed to a 'conative', which is used to imply attempt or intention:
[g=3PL.NOM]Πφε[/g] [g=2SG.ACC]τε[/g] [g=persuade.PRES-3PL]παιθο̨ντ[/g] [g=marry-PRES-INF]ηα̨μεμιν[/g] [g=3SG.ACC]ϝηε![/g]
[i]They're trying to persuade you to marry her![/i]

[g=1SG.NOM]Ιογ[/g] [g=fall.asleep.PRES-1SG]καθευσο.[/g]
[i]I'm going to try and take a nap.[/i]

The general present is formed using a paraphrasis of the irregular verb τιθμιν (from τίθεμεν, originally meaning [i]to do[/i]) and a verbal noun. The form of the verbal noun varies—with strong verbs, it is usually the o-grade plus -α; with weak verbs, a derivative in -ς with umlaut (from -σις), and with contract verbs, either the noun from which the verb is derived, or sometimes an umlauted form (from -ία.)

[g=3SG.NOM]Ϝηε[/g] [g=sleep]ηουσα[/g] [g=do.3SG]τθιτ.[/g]
[i]He's sleeping.[/i]

However, this is mostly only used in independent clauses. The bare present is used in most dependent clauses (when it is not replaced by the predicate clause):

[g=if]Τικ[/g] [g=2SG.ACC]τε[/g] [g=this-N]αυτ[/g] [g=please.PRES-3SG]αμμενισσι,[/g] [g=1SG.NOM]ιον[/g] [g=ART.M.ACC]τον[/g] [g=marriage=2SG]ηαμςτο[/g] [g=request]α̨τ[/g] [g=do.OPT-1SG]τθαιιν[/g] [g=2SG.ACC]τε[/g] [g=on]επ[/g] [g=1SG.ACC]εμε.[/g]
[i]If it pleases you, I would ask for your hand in marriage.[/i]

It is also used for some impersonal verbs:

[g=rain-3SG]Υ̨μι.[/g]
[i]It's raining.[/i]

And for imperatives:

[g=God]Θεος[/g], [g=lend]σα̨νισς[/g] [g=your-F-ACC.SG]ταν[/g] [g=strength]ϝικψυ[/g] [g=1SG.DAT]εμο̨[/g] [g=as]τθο[/g] [g=1SG.NOM]ιογ[/g] [g=my-M-ACC.PL]εμο[/g] [g=enemy]σαͱς[/g] [g=destroy.PRES-1SG]τθαιρο.[/g]
[i]God, lend me your strength as I destroy my enemies.[/i]

The future is used to refer to future events which does not imply intention or effort:

[g=ART.N-NOM.SG]Το[/g] [g=blood]ηα̨μ[/g] [g=ART.N-ACC.SG]το[/g] [g=that]κινον[/g] [g=day]αμαρ[/g] [g=flow-FUT-3SG]ρευσι.[/g]
[i]Blood will flow on that day.[/i]

The aorist has become a gnomic aspect:

[g=ART.M-NOM.SG]Ο[/g] [g=heaven]ορανς[/g] [g=ART.N-ACC.PL]τα[/g] [g=un-numbered-N]ανα̨ριθομον[/g] [g=thing]ϝερρον[/g] [g=give-AOR-3SG]εͱεν[/g] [g=man-nurturing-N]ανθροποτροφον.[/g]
[i]Heaven brings forth innumerable things to nurture man.[/i]

But the periphrastic aorist has become a perfect:

[g=pardon=1SG.DAT]Συννομαμο̨,[/g] [g=ART.F-PL.ACC]τα[/g] [g=banana]πανανα[/g] [g=not.yet]αυπο[/g] [g=in-shipping]ινσηολα[/g] [g=do.AOR-3PL]εθον[/g] [g=3PL.NOM]πφε.[/g]
[i]I'm sorry, the bananas haven't been shipped in yet.[/i]

The perfect, by contrast, has become a general preterite:

to3 senron emö3 ewewol, iyoŋ hai2 pepʰloy whe

[g=ART.N-NOM.SG]Το[/g] [g=tree]σενρον[/g] [g=1SG.DAT]εμο̨[/g] [g=threaten.PERF-3SG]εϝεϝολ,[/g] [g=1SG.NOM]ιογ[/g] [g=then]ηαι[/g] [g=set-on-fire]πεφλοͱ[/g] [g=3SG.ACC]ϝηε.[/g]
[i]The tree threatened me, so I set it on fire.[/i]

The conjugation of τθιμ 'do' is as follows:

[code]
Pres   Ind   τθιμ     τιτς     τθιτ     τιττον     τιθμιν     τιττ      τιθινθ
       Opt   τθαιιν   τθαις    τθαιε    τθαιτον    τθαιμιν    τθαιτ     τθαιιν
       Imp            τιθε     τιττο    τιττον                τιττ      τιθινθο
Aor    Ind   εθικ     εθιχ     εθικ     εττον      εθμιν      εττε      εθον
       Opt   θαιιν    θαις     θαιε     θαιτον     θαιμιν     θαιτ      θαιιν
       Imp            θε       θετο     θετον                 θετ       θενθο
[/code]